There's no hard and fast rules with kids - they're all different. With some kids, a measured and targetted form of corporal punishment, in the cases where the kid's behaviour really is out of order, can be a very effective way of correcting the behavioural pattern. In other case, it can have the opposite effect.

It's not the same although many appear to deliberately attempt to conflate the two. It's a corrective measure you have in your toolbox, but it's not guaranteed to work, any more than sitting the child down for a long understanding chat is guaranteed to work. Kids are humans as well, and as such, they respond differently to different things.. and some of them truly are, total assholes

No, if you're generating class images its generating ~155 similar images to your images in a classification folder. Its used to expand a dataset (works great for replicating porn you like though with minor changes). After 155 it will cache latents (if you chose to) and then start the steps for actual training.

Each epoch is 1 pass through your entire dataset both ways. So if you choose 10 epochs for training and have 100 images you can see your steps fly up.

LORAs exceed at small input data sets for fast training.
Or at least from what I understand, anyone can correct me.
